{"questionId":"17585","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Sungwon plays a game where she rolls a fair <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math>-sided die and spins a fair spinner with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;equal sectors. During each turn in the game, the die is rolled once and the spinner is spun&nbsp;once. The <strong>score</strong> for each turn is the sum of the two results. For example, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> on the die and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;on the spinner would receive a score of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/65e29e27f26620caab7fc3b68645c45a4fbb4a64.png\"></p>\n<p>The following diagram represents the sample space.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/2271b8c7dc09a85f3268b381837c412f15575320.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Sungwon takes a second turn.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p style=\"text-align:left;\">Find the probability that Sungwon scores greater than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math> on both of her first two turns.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>18</mn><mn>24</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mn>18</mn><mn>24</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em><br></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for the square of <em>their</em> probability in part (a).<br></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>563</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfrac><mn>324</mn><mn>576</mn></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5625</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>56</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>%</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)</strong><em><strong> (C2)</strong></em><br></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><strong>Note:</strong> Follow through from part (a), provided <em>their</em> answer is less than or equal to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>.</span></p>\n<p><em><strong><span class=\"mjpage\">[2 marks]</span></strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"17585","referenceCode":"19N.1.SL.TZ0.T_9b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the probability that Sungwon scores greater than 4 on both of her first two turns.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.5—Probability concepts, expected numbers","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.6—Combined, mutually exclusive, conditional, independence, prob diagrams"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}